**5.3a** The present value of an investment refers to the present value of all future cash flow of the investment given a specific time frame and specific rate. 

It can be solved using the basic present value equation which is given as:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Present value}&=\dfrac{\text{Future value}}{(1+\text{rate})^\text{time}}
\end{aligned}$$

**5.3b** The rule of 72 is basically a rule for estimating the amount of time before an investment doubles in value. It is named the Rule of 72 since you will divide 72 by the rate and the answer will give an approximate number of years before the investment doubles. 

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Time before investment doubles}&=\dfrac{72}{\text{rate}}
\end{aligned}$$
